transcript: â€‰ Marketing Models & Mindcraft Chapter 21: Media Performance     No. 323 / 544  Media Saturation Threshold Theory     Author/Source: Multiple contributors, notably Herbert E. Krugman (three-exposure theory), John Philip Jones (short-term advertising strength), Erwin Ephron (recency planning)     Summary: Media Saturation Threshold Theory identifies the point where additional ad exposures yield diminishing returns or backlash. It combines:     Effective Frequency:Â Minimum exposures needed for message retention (typically 3-10)    Wear-Out Effect:Â Creative fatigue causing irritation or tune-out    Category Norms:Â High-involvement products (cars) tolerate more frequency than low-involvement (snacks)      Optimal thresholds vary by:     PlatformÂ (TikTok ads wear out faster than OOH)    CreativeÂ (narrative spots last longer than repetitive jingles)    AudienceÂ (loyalists tolerate more exposures than new prospects)      Brand Examples:     BrewDogÂ â€“ Limited punk-themed YouTube pre-rolls to 4 exposures/month after data showed craft beer fans perceived higher frequency as "selling out." ChobaniÂ â€“ Caps Greek yogurt TV spots at 5 exposures/week in key markets, using Nielsen data to balance reach and irritation. Dove Men+CareÂ â€“ Found 7 was the optimal monthly Facebook ad frequency for male audiences before negative sentiment spiked. EtsyÂ â€“ Uses A/B testing to determine handmade goods display ads peak at 3 impressions/user/week before click-through rates drop. Fenty BeautyÂ â€“ Rotates Instagram Story creatives every 72 hours to avoid makeup tutorial ad fatigue observed in Gen Z.      GoProÂ â€“ Limits adventure sports YouTube ads to 2 exposures/user/month, as core users value "authentic" low-frequency messaging. HÃ¤agen-DazsÂ â€“ Discovered luxury ice cream ads on Hulu perform best at 6 exposures over 2 weeksâ€”higher frequencies cheapen the brand. YetiÂ â€“ Outdoor gear digital ads follow a "3-5-1" rule: 3 creatives, 5 exposures max, 1-month cool-off period per audience segment.

It's bad, I know, but I need to check that there have been no disasters overnight that need my attention. I then brush my teeth and put on some SPF. Garnier Ambre Solaire SPF 50+ Sensitive Advanced Sun Cream Face & Body is my current go-to. My morning soundtrack is anything by BeyoncÃ©, I love the latest album even more after seeing her live. I also take a shot of Symprove before I leave. 4.50am My gym is only a six-minute drive from my house. In summer I wear shorts and a bra top to work out in. Most of my kit comes fromÂ lululemon,Â Oner Active andÂ Sweaty Betty. I work out a minimum of five times a week, mixing it up with cardio, strength training and PT sessions. When I am strength training, I wear Nike Metcons and for running, I wear Nike Journey. 6am I have my protein shake as soon as I get back from the gym. It's a mixture of protein powder, collagen and creatine with water. I then go and give my children a cuddle before heading into the shower. My favourite body wash is Naturium The Glow GetterÂ  Body Wash Â followed by theÂ body butter. I go in quickly with a spritz of my favourite scent,Â Encelade by Marc-Antoine Barrois. On my face, I useÂ Paula's Choice Skin Perfecting 2% BHA Liquid Exfoliant followed byÂ Koba moisturiser. Make-up starts withÂ Danessa Myricks Beauty Yummy Skin Blurring Balm Powder and I always use Fenty'sÂ  foundation â€“ it's the best. I use theÂ By Terry eye liner and I mix blushers fromÂ Merit andÂ NARS. Finally, I set everything withÂ Charlotte Tilbury's setting spray and in the evenings, I use the one fromÂ ONE/SIZE. 7am I'm definitely a magpie but my style is also defined by clean lines. I find Lisa Ing Marinelli's take on fashion really inspiring â€“ she's someone who also has a corporate job but embraces her personal style. If I had an endless budget, I would go to Tove every season. I just bought one of my favourite summer dresses from the brand. I'm also a big fan of Rejina Pyo. On the high street, I love COS and Massimo Dutti. I only give myself about ten minutes to get dressed before I have to leave the house â€“ either to get the kids to school or catch the train to work....
